review_text: Great food here
Went for dinner few weeks ago. The sekuwa was so badd that i still get nightmares about it

Truly delicious jhol momo. The server even provided us with a bit of broth to take home as we couldn t get enough. Unlimited masala tea will have us buzzing through the night!  If you are coming from LaGuardia, don t miss this stop on your way into town. Directly across from the Roosevelt Avenue/Jackson Heights station, it was a perfect reminder of the things I love about this city. Small and crowded, with authentic cuisine and beautiful flavors!

A must go to place to go for really good Nepali food made with love and tradition. And their MoMo is the best especially the goat . Anyone who comes to newyork on vacation must visit this restaurant before leaving back home and the owner is a wonderful powerful woman who welcomes everyone.

I would give 0 star if I could. The restaurant is so so busy but yet the management is the worst. We had chicken jhol momo which have no taste at all. And the more drawbacks was the management and the person sitting in the counter. Seeing the name Nepali and this kind of thing, it s so so disappointing.

Ordered the chicken jhol momos, steamed paneer and chili curry chicken. They were amazing and juicy! The fried goat momos were a little dry but once you add the sauce, it came to life. The fried rice was also SO good. And prices were so good - def want to come back and try other items on the menu
Good expression
Cute restaurant with variety of momos.

Honestly one of the best Momos I ever had. Got Goat Momo Jhola (soup) and Buffalo momo. Amazing!  Must try . However, the Roti was cold and stale , lost1 star because of that. Hopefully ongoing you correct this as it would have been 5/5. Also loved the fact the owner Yamuna was in music videos that were playing in her restaurant, very amusing!

Best and tastiest  momos I have ever had within reasonable  price.   The environment  was good, they have rest room too. The service  was a little bit late however  I was okay with that, they served a sel roti during my waiting time and that was complimentary . The food was fresh and warm.
Got the goat momo soup and it was amazing! The group was super flavourful and the portions were very large. Great place to eat! Will be back again
Got the Jhol momo and C. momos. Jhol momo was a bit lacking; 7/10. But the C. momos were great. Good spice and not just heat, crispy texture. 8 or 8.5/10.

Best  & tastiest  momos I have ever had within reasonable  price .  The environment  is good too  and service was a bit slow  however I was okay with that as I had no hurry that day. The amount of food  was good.

No matter what their jhol momo are so good but today we went there for thali. Trust me this will be my first and last thali over there. First we need to wait 30 min just to give order then we again need to wait for 45mins for the food.. Chicken thali and beef sukuti thali - only the pickle was okay but thali looks awful with less amount of food . No server, every server will be inside of the kitchen for nothing. We need to wait for another 30 mins just to ask for water cause waitress are more busy running to kitchen.. And also we were embarrassed to ask for extra rice because the waitress busy running to the kitchen.

Food is really yummy. I like this spot for their jhol momos. The service is alright, they are kind. So far, two of the times I ve been here they got my order wrong and brought me the wrong dish. But they fixed it and brought me what I ordered, just a little longer wait. I recommend chicken jhol momos, sel roti, and masala tea.

Nestled right in front of the Roosevelt avenue subway station, Nepali  Banncha Ghar offers a taste of Nepal with its delectable momos and home style cooking. As you step inside, the aroma of spices and steaming dumplings welcomes you, setting the stage for a delightful culinary experience. The menu features an array of momo options, from the classic chicke, lamb and beef along with vegetable and paneer. Each dumpling is meticulously crafted, with thin, delicate wrappers and flavorful fillings that burst with every bite. Not to miss is the Jhol momo with silky, spicy savory broth with incredible momos, perfect for a rainy or chilly day! Apart from the momos, this place also offers a variety of traditional Nepali dishes, such as thukpa and sel roti, providing a unique experience in one of the most diverse boroughs of New York
AMAZING    BEST Nepali food in the area. The Momo winner   The owner is awesome

On a chilly winter day, my quest for the hot momos led me to Bhanchha Ghar. The menu was adorned with a variety of Nepalese dishes. We started with the Wai Wai chat, and what a delightful surprise it turned out to be! Perfect spice level and the crunch made it an instant star on our table. Veg Thukpa,  was a perfect choice for the chilly weather, satisfying both the body and the soul. Our momo adventure took an unexpected turn when the staff brought us the steamed momos with Jhol. Initially apprehensive about the twist, the Jhol turned out to be a game-changer, elevating the momos. While I wouldnt claim these were the absolute best momos Ive had, the Jhol added a delicious dimension. Overall, it was a good experience that left us with warm memories and contented taste buds.
food is really tasty. worth the trip. nice service. halal food Kid-friendliness: there is a sink wash hands and chairs to sit like adults. good prices Food : 5/5 |
Very nice place with extremely good food. Vegetarian options: Good Wheelchair accessibility: Good
Surreal how good the food is here. Will definitely be back!
Very authentic. Reminded me of my time in Nepal.
Delicious food at great prices. A must-visit.
Waited for 40 minutes for momos and and when we asked for an update they seemed to be lost and asked our order again. Not a pleasant experience.
Good foood for the price
Good one! reasonable price

I got some steamed veg momos for breakfast! This was one of the place that was open early and serving veg option! The momos were really soft, and the sauce was quite good as well! Definitely be back here if I m in the area! The momos are reasonably priced and quantity was above par as well!
Vegetarian options: Good lunch And dinner Food : 4/5
Very nice service and food,I loved it Vegetarian options: Very nice service and food Parking: Roosevelt and 75 street
I love food  & nice service
Great service and delicious food Parking: Awesome Food : 5/5 |

We had the chicken and the goat jhol Momo ( which comes in a soup base). They use halal meat. The soup was the same across the two jhol bowls, in the chicken you could not really taste the chicken but the goat had a very distinctive taste along with the soup. Atmosphere was pretty nice and while the service was slow it was because the food was made per order.
Jhola MoMo was Good .
The best thali I ve had in the States. We got mutton, chicken and fish thali - none of them left any room for complaint. Works definitely come back for more later.
The best momos I ve had in New York. Try chilli veg momos and jhol momos. I do not recommend thali Vegetarian options: Veg momos and paneer momos are the best
Incredible

Probably our favorite momo place in Jackson Heights. It s affordable, they take credit card, and the food is amazing. The soup momos (momo jole) are excellent, and the tea is quite good, especially for only $1, though it s self-serve and they run out of it often. The sel roti is also a must it s basically a fried bagel, or a Turkish simit, with some excellent sauce. The woman next to us had momo that looked like it was soaked in chili sauce; I ll be getting that next time. Like many places in Jackson Heights you kinda gotta assert yourself with the wait staff, and it can take awhile to be seen, but it s not excessive. Besides, the food is worth it anyway.
Had both the beef and goat momo in curry broth. Both are very good but the goat is the better one if we can only have one.

Got Goat Bhuttan Thali, was totally bland, no taste at all, the side dish come not hot enough, it s cool, and the service wise, the guy in the front counter need proper training for the customer service. He was intentionally rude. overall not a good restaurant at all.. Definitely not going again .
Amazing chicken momos and spicy red sauce
Nepali restaurant and halal food, and many vegetarian foods.
Good
Momo crawl winners for a reason. Jhol momo is stupid delicious
I am really disappointed cause I found steel in my chicken chowmeen and unfortunately I ate it, was not expected  hope you guys take care of it from next time.

1. I ordered a Jhol Steamed Momo online. They stood me up for approximately 40 minutes to hand over my order. 2. Apart, from this, I have also experienced them serving momo consisting of lots of fat and skin. 3. Chicken thali was served cold and had late refills on it.
I had chicken khana set and it was just okay ..i was there on new year eve2023  .usually this place was better but this time so disappointed.only best were jhol momo .
I order to go and they took an hr to go plus I didn t get what I actually order and missing item what I paid for . Dinning is good food come fast but please do not order to go!!. Food

Nothing was good. The chowmein and fried rice was sweet. Thukpa was just boiled noodles with boiled veggies. I do not recommend this place. The guy at the front register is rude too, customer service is not good.
The paneer jhol momo was to die for, the orange broth is spiced and flavored with magic. The veg jhol momo was also pretty good.

Raw food. Told server that its uncooked. She replied  that s how it is . We told her to show it to the chef because she was claiming it false. Turns out chef agrees with us and later she took it and chef recooked it. Its was a grilled meat. They fried it when recooking. Very DISAPPOINTED! Jhol momo had no flavor and was bland. Also, their chai tea was super bland. No tea leaves and not the right ratio for the milk. Super watery. I m sorry but we are never coming back Service was not great as well. For service 3/5 For food 0/5
Me and my friends were there for lunch and had a best experience.. If you wanna try authentic nepalese food this is the place. Also our server Roshni and Kanchan were very nice and helpful.
Oh my god. This place is so good. Thali was so so so good.  Our servers Kanchan and Roshani were so nice to us. Thank you:)
Brings back a lot of memories from Nepal. Server Kanchan and Roshni were great. Loved the food and ambiance.

Our first experience having momo.  The spicy sauce and momo wontons were delicious.  The spicy sauce adds such a great punch of flavor.  Right across the street from the bus terminal from LaGuardia, easy access
Authentic and fairly priced. Would recommend.

This place is overhyped. The service was also not that great, you have to wait for a long time for the server to respond to you. The food is also okayish, the momos outside the restaurant in the cart are better.

I could get the real desi cartlike food taste after a long time. The food came in good portion, just the right taste and very reasonably priced. We ordered the bread, mixed spaghetti, jhol momo and fried momo. We found them really good! Would definitely go for another time.
Service was good. Food was okay. Felt a little greasy. Tried only the Sel roti. Cant talk about other food. But thats Nepali street style. Very Limited street parking.
10/10 I ll miss this but vow to return. Goat Soup delicious, Goat Roti Thali delicious, the sweet tea? Get outta here scrumptious. Friendliest of staff, best food in the neighborhood.

Went there on a busy Friday night the ambiance gives old Indian restaurant vibes, which is kinda cool imo, I didn t like the jhol(curry) with the momos although momos were delicious. Lassi was quite good too. The service was good.
Tasted like a real home cooked dal bhat and masu. I will never go to other Nepali restaurants in Jackson Heights for Thali.
Food was good but not what it used to be, quality has been deteriorated customer service was not good, owner was so rude and not behaving nicely , had a very bad experience
The Jhol MoMo are incredibly delicious! Great value for money as well
Best MoMos I ever had!!
Today who pick up the phone doesn t have manners to speak with customer.we are customer that we pay and want good things not free.don t try to give attitude with customer
A good nepalese foods available. Weekly nepali singing programs held.
One of the worst customer service, arrogant receptionist.unplasant faces. Need to train how to deal with customers. Food
IT IS very good
Overall I wouldn t recommend this restaurant. The service is extremely low.

This place has turned from a really decent place to the worst. A drunk guy swearing foul profanities yet staff did not even bother to stop him. Waited 15 min, yet no one came to take an order. It used to provide close to authentic Nepali cuisine but now the place is a mess.

This is authentic Nepali food in Queens...which felt like Nepal.  That means friendly, funky and slow.  The staff treated us to a delicious  sel roti, a fried rice ring with mouth warming garlic chutney Our chicken momos were simple and tasty...mine had flavorful broth added.  Generous helpings.   The Masala tea was lovely.  Very affordable.
Decent place for Nepali food, usually little crowded and we wish sanitation could have been little better.
Try the Chicken Jhol momo and the sel roti
Hands down five stars!
The food is soo good. Thank you I will visit again if I m back to New York

Really authentic Nepali food in NYC. Cool people. A bit noisy outside because of the train. You meet many Nepali people. Update: I have chaged from 5 to 4. the next few times I went to eat, and I didnt feel the comfort with the test of goat meat, kind of smelly, and bad taste. Also the MOMO was too oversized. Seems like people are changing.

They have pretty good momos, loved the goat momos in usual. Update Sep 26 2023 We ordered lamb momos to go and they served us uncooked lamb. We re worried about it now as it might have some microorganism pathogens
Must try momos

Amazing food. Im upset that I didnt come here at my hungriest, because everything was so tasty. The paneer jholi momos, which come in a thick soup, are so delicious, and the chili fries are a perfect t late night snack. The staff are extremely friendly. Definitely worth a trip!
Service was really bad waited 2+ hours not worth it, the chicken thali was so gross dont recommend at all. Jhol momo was okay but not worth the wait.
The jhol momo was good but I don t recommend any thali
We ordered Sel, dhedo, Thali and momo. Everything was really tasty. Good service! Highly recommend!!
Mouthwatering food and friendly smile

Disappointed that the restaurant claims to be halal but sells alcohol. Even if the meat is halal, it s not halal for Muslims to dine at an area where alcohol is served. While the food I had was great, unfortunately I will not be returning and I would advise other Muslims to do the same unless they decide to no longer serve alcohol. Dietary restrictions: Although the meat is halal, they serve alcohol which no longer makes the restaurant a halal option to dine at.
Goat jhol momo and chicken jhol momo are delicious Kid-friendliness: Nice behaviour Food : 5/5 |
Great authentic momos for amazing price!! Very generous portions of momos per plate
Divine!! Come here to get your momo fix.

Our Nepali culinary experience was exceptional. The Nepali Jhol Momo, Sel Roti, and Nepali Thali transported us to Nepals heartland. Flavors were authentic, a true delight. However, the service was a bit lacking. Multiple prompts were needed to get attention. Despite this, the remarkable food overshadowed the minor setback. In summary, this restaurant offers an authentic taste of Nepal. Though service could improve, the culinary journey was truly memorable. I would highly recommend.
I order  two shalrot  to go and it takes me like one hour to be ready , service is not good , I don t like the service at all .

The food tastes okay overall but is too salty, so its not worth waiting 30-45 minutes for. The goat momos dont taste any different from beef, and the chow meins home-made flavor is just ruined by being too salty. The mango lassi was alright. Not too sweet, decent flavor, and a nice level of thickness. I would recommend the halal (Ive only noticed one specify it and I dont remember this ones name) truck for momo near the subway entrance on the three way intersection if you want momo. It tastes good (pretty similar, just less salty) and has pretty much no wait. Kid-friendliness: Noisiness is good for kids but not too sure theyd be willing to wait so long.

The food is good but the girl who works their shes supper nice she looks young and seeing her work almost every day is unbelievable I usually go their every day to get milk tea and fried veg momo every morning and the way she talks is so sweet she seems like shes 18 to 19 years old the food is really good she even put free sel roti for me today since  my order was late keep up little girl your future is supper bright

I came here with family after hearing good things and because everything is halal. We tried a variety of things but the best thing, by far, are the momos. We ordered a bunch of chicken, beef, and shrimp ones in different styles and they were all great - fresh and steaming hot. The other stuff like the thalis weren t worth getting in my opinion. The servers work hard but it can get a little chaotic as it gets busy. If you re coming here, I recommend sticking to the momos and possibly some sides dishes.
You can have tasty Nepali food.
Good environment and food

Their service is the worst. I was very hungry and went there to eat momo. After a while, one guy came and sat at the same table with me, although there were a lot of table empty, but I didn t care at all. He also ordered momo, but surprisingly, his order came first and he almost finished his momo, but mine didn t arrived. Had to ask the waiter twice, and every time he would say,  ahh huss ekaixin ma hunxa . I didn t want to be rude, so kept patience. Then after a while, the owner noticed and asked the waiter about my order and only then the momo arrived. Wasn t the first time facing that kind of service there, but it surely was the last one.

Me and my friends went there  to have a Nepali thali and the service was worst . It seems like not a restaurant more like a local Nepali khaga ghar and the waiter was so rude and unprofessional. We asked waiter to add some side dishes for thali but they bring at once . We had to ask them 3 times and at the end they bring something.The taste of the food was also bad and at the end we realized that we just wasted our money . At the same price we should have went somewhere nice   . Just be careful while going there . And the water at the jug / mug on the table was smelling so bad . I don t recommend someone who wants to eat something there because the environment was not clean and you goona feel awkward while dine in there . Thanks
Amazing veg momos!
Chicken Jhol Momo - 4/5 Chicken Steam Momo - 4/5 Chicken C Momo - 3/5 Chicken Fried Momo - 3/5 Potato chili- 3/5 Chicken Thali - 3/5 Chicken Sekuwa - 2/5

I echo the earlier review of Jason Andrew. While the food is amazing - even better than in Nepal and probably the best in NYC, their service is pathetic. One day, I ordered online and it was delivered on time. But, on two occasions earlier this month, I was there to dine in (together with family members), nobody would come to take orders. They would take up to one hour to serve the food -- that even after asking and reminding numerous times. When I was there solo, at one point, the wait was too long that I thought of leaving the place without eating. I left in the end, half-eaten.

I did not satisfied with this resturent bCoZ I go alone there I seated there about 40 minutes but they did not come to ask me what to serve and then when I say the one waiter to bring bottled water he bring water and get aggressive towards me they only care for group costumer not single costumer waiter service is not good for whom who go single
Food and service was good. Best part is, its halal  . Ate the goat thali. Liked it.
Good was good and tasted authentic. I would definitely go back.
Very good authentic momos Beef steamed and beef soup with momos was our choice Prices are very generous. Im definitely coming back for more Momos Vegetarian options: Lots of vegan choices

The food was really good. We tried momos and sel roti. However, when we were eating, we noticed a man arguing in the kitchen. He was bleeding heavily in the back of the head. This scene was a terrifying. To have someone bleeding in the kitchen after an argument/ fight is a BIG NO. To matter how good the food is, how would you eat once you see someone bleeding heavily in the kitchen? To my shock, nobody called 911 and the person kept a ice pack and walked out of the restaurant after sometime. When someone is injured, you remove them from the kitchen and treat them immediately. Period. This experience was traumatic to me
Delicious food and lovely staff! The level of spice was excellent and the flavors were rich. Well definitely be back again sooner than later.
Service was slow, price is reasonable, veg and paneer momos were delicious. The chutneys were available at the table, and were okay in taste.

The food is delicious but the service is horribly slow. The restaurant keo Dietary restrictions: They had a spicy pepper for the whole dish but didnt tell me it was spicy and i ate it one shot and my mouth exploded. Not happy about that Food : 5/5 |

the waiter there was so nice. 10/10. he even gave me a free sel roti. I ordered a mixed chowmein, jhol momo and something else I forgot the name of (sorry). I really liked the mixed chowmein. it did take a long time for the food to prepare tho
Excellent beef momos, but Sel Roti was even better.
THE BEST

The only good thing here is sel roti. So we made a big order of sel roti and we were told it would take more than  30 minutes: one hour later, my husband went to pick up and they never put in the order. Instead of giving us fresh one like discussed, they tried to give us stale cold sel roti, all 15 of them!! Service was extremely bad, the lady was rude as hell. Didn t even listen and walked away while my husband was asking questions nicely,
This place is amazing!!!  Funny, cool waiters too!  ;)
Great place to experience Nepalese food with many Nepalese natives eating there.
Good taste.

Excellent food.  Theyve won the momo crawl several years in a row for good reason, but the thalia and baji plates were also fantastic. Small, less than a dozen tables, but if youre in Jackson Heights and like traditional Nepali food, this is a place to try.

Worst experience. I ordered sel roti for pick up but when I got there it wasn t ready. I paid and was waiting for my order and I saw the guy getting my order with bare hands, literally no gloves . I also ordered steam Momo and found hair on it. Never ever going back again
Loved the chilli momos and the jhol momos. You should definitely try it if you love spicy food. Sel roti however, I felt was a bit dry, not sure if thats how it is supposed to be.
They forgot about our order, served our white wine at room temperature. Terrible service.
They are fraud. Total cost of food was $46.67 per person and I added $5 tip. But they modified the tip and I am charged $57.67. This is not just for me. Other 2 friends had same experience.
This is the worst Nepali restaurant, they charge TAX on the TIPS and the jhol momo was the worst.
Excellent quality of food
Steamed Goat momo is very flavourful and best one Ive had so far.

I sat there on a table waiting for my friends to join me and Didi brought me a fresh, hot sel roti to munch on as I waited. She did not want to charge me for that. This hospitality that reminds me of home dictates my experience here so I may be biased but everything, starting from Jhol Momo to Sel Roti to Sekuti was superb. Taste, presentation and freshness, was on point  We were a big group and ordered in so many parts (apologies) but the servers were always friendly and smiling. My favorite was definitely sel roti and Jhol Momo. I will keep going back as long as I am in NYC.
Great local and authentic Nepalese spot. Highly recommend any of the thali dishes that come with an assortment of dishes and rice or roti!

We tried the chicken, shrimp, and vegetarian momos - all are good. I personally love the warming tomato-based soup of the jhol momo. The Tibetan butter tea was delicious, but the cardamom tea was a little bland. Service is a little slow and they are busy with dine-in and take-out orders. Conveniently located next to the subway station.

Seeing as we were staying in Jackson Heights on a trip to New York, my friend and I found it only appropriate to sample some of the area s best food. Following a brief search, we decided on Nepali Bhancha Ghar - a five time five time winner of the annual momo crawl. Planning to spend a large part of our day eating we decided to split a single dish and a mango lassi each. After some consultation we opted for a beef jhol momo and enjoyed the calming music playing in the background. Lassi s were first to arrive, adequately priced at 4 dollars, and consisting of a tasty combination of salty yogurt and sweet mango. Momo s arrived soon after, floating in a delightfully aromatic broth and topped with coriander. We dug in, dipping the momos in the broth before biting into them, and were rewarded with a delicious texture and a fresh, warm and delicately spiced filling. The broth was equally tasty, with hints of acidity and additional freshness from coriander. Whilst we only tried out a singular item, we were both very impressed with our experience, and given the opportunity, I would happily revisit to try out the rest of Nepali Bhancha Ghar s presumably impressive menu.
Excellent
Can t go wrong with anything on the menu. And if you re lucky, the owner will take pictures of your table in amazement when you order half the food in the place. Delicious across the board.
Theres a reason their momos win competitions!
The goat momo were delicious so the mango juice! Loved it all
Highly recommended
I asked for beef chowmien charged me $9, THERE IS NO BEEF IN IT and the old lady at the register has no sense of customer service at all. Mean old lady
Environment is okay, jhol momo is good but the beef was undercooked and stiff.

I am now a beef momo jhola. The soup is tasty and just the right amount of spicy. Perfect for the cold weather. We tried the sel roti, its underwhelming. The fried chicken dumplings were ok. My friend loved the paneer fried momos.

I just spend $60 in ubereats from this place and it was disappointing. My momo didnt came with any sauce, my roti was not a fresh one like they used to have. It was a ready made one from patel  brother. My roti s tarkari was salty and very watery. I ve ordered multiple times from these guys and never had any issues but looks like they have changed their staff. My waiwai sadeko was just buja in it. There was no waiwai in thier. What a waste of money !
Veg fried rice is not good. Veg thali and momos are good.
If youre looking for good Nepali food and service in NYC, this is the worst place to go. Items are missing, theres hair in the food, and service is so late. Theres no way Im going back.
Amazing traditional food.

This place offers one of the authenticate taste of nepali food. Do try their veggie fired as well as steamed momos. Nepali thali is also interesting and adequate for a person. They took quite a considerable amount of time to cook food. Vegetarian options: Veggie steamed momos Veggie fried momos Vegetarian nepali thali
This place is a gem. Ordered jhol momo, sel roti, and masala tea. Incredible flavors,and prices too. I LOVE THIS PLACE
Very bad food
Nice

Eh the waitress forgot our order it was almost an hour or so by the time we got our 2 order of momo s. They took forever  to get the bill. Goat jhol momo was really bad. Ive had better. Chicken momo was okay. Atmosphere wise the establishment had a distinctively bad smell the kind of smell you get at a meat market.  Overall not a pleasant experience.  Ive had better Nepali food before. I would not revisit this establishment.

Ordered the beef and chicken jhol momo, good portions for the price and the jhol was not too salty. Momo are definitely bigger in size compared to the other restaurants around the area. Service was fast and friendly.

One of the bad service I ever see, I felt very bad for the server guy he was literally only one who was taking care of more than 10 tables, who ever owner is he/she needs to hire more waiters. And the food was too salty . Also, once s you done to make payment you need to wait more than 15 minutes. Waist of time and money . It s my first and last visiting  in Nepali bhancha ghar.

Stopped by today because this place was a consecutive winner of the momo crawl. Service was a bit awkward because we were seated in the basement. We were the only ones there and the staff was mainly on the first floor, but the food was very good. Highly recommmend the thentuk and momo jhola  the dishes were extremely filling and soups were complex in flavor.

It is a nice Nepali restaurant around the neighborhood. I was basically looking for a momo place to try and came across this. They are located at the prime location of Jackson Heights and their interior is nice compared to the other places around. I felt like their service time is super slow, so if you are planning on visiting this place DO NOT GO WHILE YOU ARE STARVING! I absolutely loved their chicken jhola momo. It tasted different and the broth was full of flavors. I would suggest adding some chili with the broth. Also tried their beef steamed momo but that kind of seemed average.
Excellent place
Favorite place for soupy Momos! Try the Goat Momo Jhola

Great food. But poor service. Maybe it s a language barrier. My first experience was memorable to came back for more. Like, literally I came back the next night. The mushroom soup was ideal for a cold rainy night. The steamed chicken momo s or fried goat momo s were perfect especially for an introduction to the cuisine. The veggie chow mein was well flavored but not too spicy you could not enjoy. I attempted to come back the next night to try more items from their menu but my server who I had the night before fumbled my order and his flippancy towards service meant I waited almost 45 mins in a empty restaurant for 2 out of the ordered 6 dishes to not arrive. No apology no rationale. He was more interested in playing YouTube videos than actually attending to needs of customers not including myself. He s even on iG outside smoking before we were finished. I traveled a hr to be dissatisfied with the service not cuisine. So this will not happen again. Take out if you must.
Good place
Jhol momo (5/5)

Good food at excellent prices. The sel roti (friend dough) is a must try as an appetizer. I enjoyed the platter (thalis) and the momo in broth. The least favorite part was the fried fish in the platter, because it was too small and had many bones. The service was nice enough, they came to check on us a few times.

The food is great but the service is below par. Communication and organization between the ordering staff and chefs need to be clearer. Ordering queues take longer than average (>1hr) because of poor communication. Please fix this!
The momo are great. Super juicy and flavorful. My favorites were the jhol momo and the fried beef momo. The goat Thali was also delicious.
Momo was great.

Worst experience!! The plates, cups, and spoons had grease (probably of meat). I dont think they even bothered to wash it properly. They wouldnt give you computerized bill. The server was very rude. If he excuses his behavior saying that he is underpaid, he has no rights to take out his frustration on the customers. No manners. Never going back. Never recommending this to anyone!! Really disappointed.
The broth for johl momo is amazing, but the spices for momo is not that great. However the combination is amazing. A mediocre food place but definitely a very authentic restaurant for Nepali food.

I went here with work colleagues after seeing a review of it on Instagram. Nepali Bhanchha Ghar is an award winning restaurant for momos having won the annual Momo Crawl 4 years in a row. Therefore I had to try them for myself. I was impressed with their variety of momos. Traditional ones like beef and chicken. Modern ones such as buffalo and goat. Seafood ones like fish and shrimp. In addition to vegetarian options such as potato aloo and paneer. There were so many to chose from. I ordered the beef, chicken, buffalo, shrimp and goat momos. They were all very juicy and submerged in a flavorful broth. The goat momo is probably the most unique momo I ever tasted. They werent the best momos Ive ever had, but the quality and taste are very good. They definitely win points for their momo variety and delicious broth.

Food was pretty good and hit the spot for an early morning. Restaurant is very authentic and we would like to come back for lunch or dinner sometime.

This is the sort of restaurant and food for which the phrase  if you know, you know  was created -  it is the winner of Queen s momo crawl for multiple years and a gathering place for members of New York s Nepalese community. The food is always freshly prepared and amongst the best you can have in Jackson Heights and possibly elsewhere. The momos - both the plain steamed ones and the  jhol  momos which come submerged in a spicy, brothy soup - are juicy, with a perfect skin (neither too thin nor too thick) and immensely addictive. But the momos aren t all that you should come for. There are the thalis that make you feel like you are eating in somebody s home, and the Nepalese Sel Roti, which is a mildly sweet, fried rice flour bread, that would be quite unlike any other you may have eaten. And the place itself has a kind, soothing ambience which makes you feel at home and away from all the noise and bustle of Jackson Heights.

I came here twice last year, the first time, we came in, sat down (4 of us) ordered our food. after 45 minutes, our food was not prepared and we waited. Finally our friend who spoke Nepali said that the 2 workers were arguing about who was supposed to start cooking. When the food arrived, it was actually amazing. So waiting almost an hour wasnt bad because the quality was amazing. 2nd time, we came and sat. We ordered momos and the cold ramen dish thing. Food came quicker, but was not as good. The momos were grainy at some parts and felt undercooked, I couldnt eat the rest after a while because i started to have a gag reflex. The language barrier for us was bad because it was hard to communicate with the staff because we dont speak Nepali. Now that brings us to today. We placed a large order through seamless, vegetable fried rice no egg, momos, 3 chicken thukpas, 1 vege thukpa and a few other dishes. Our coworker accidentally order thentuk instead of thukpa, but thats fine. The issue was how they sent the food to us. Everything was tighlty packed and in several bags. Meaning 4 soup containers, on top of one another, each was boiling hot in plastic containers which are definitely not meant for this type of heat. When we got our food, 3 of the 4 soup containers were broken, Broth was everywhere in the bag. The chicken Thali was bad, the pieces were very small, contained bone and were not edible for the most part. The sauce from that container also spilled into the bag. The lentil sauce also spilled into the bags as well. The fried rice wasnt tasty nor was the vegetable soup. I have to say, myself along with my coworkers were disappointed and will probably not order from again in the near future. They didnt package the items properly. It wasnt the fault of the delivery person, as they had everything in a cooler. Seeing as how the previous 2 experiences were, I can only fault the restaurant.

This is one of the best hidden gems in all of New York City, and I almost didnt want to reveal it to the world just to keep it to myself! I randomly stumbled upon this restaurant about 5 years back, when it was literally just a hole in the wall spot on a side street, nestled between a barber shop and a meat store. I wouldnt have even known about it if it wasnt for the wonderful aroma of the food. I generally have a rule that if the food smells good at a restaurant, you should at least try one item, or that particular item that they are cooking that you smelled. I dont remember what the first thing I ordered here, but simply put, I was completely blown away. The old lady owner of the place (referred simply as Didi) was hand making dumplings (which later I learned are Momos), and was very enthusiastic about me being there for the first time, and suggested a myriad of items to try. I only tried a few, but shouldve taken her advice! If youve never had it, Nepalese food is similar to Indian food, but its also vastly different, unique, and full of big robust flavors. Theres a few things I love about this place. First of all, they do not try to Americanize their cuisine, and tone down the spice or flavors. This means that some items will def have some spice and heat, but its never overwhelming, and not everything is spicy. Second, the portions are really good, and you will be full quite easily and affordably. This is local working people food, so the price is very reasonable, and the quantity is supple. Lastly, I dont eat any pork  and this place also doesnt cook any pork products, and their meat is halal! If you are coming here for the first time, I suggest you start with a few sel rotis (deep fried rice flour rings with a spicy salsa like sauce), some selection of Momos (go for the jhol Momo which bathes in a spicy broth), choyela, and any other items you may want to try. My favorite is beef shkuti, which are dry beef pieces that are cooked on a wok with several spices, and the flavors build the more you chew. If you are really hungry, go for one of their signature Thalis, which are several vegetable items, Daal, rice, pickles, some type of green veg, and meat/fish item of your choosing. Even if you are not a vegetarian, getting the veggie thali may just end up converting you, as youll see how much flavor can be packed into simple vegetables. Bhanchaa Ghar is a special place. A few years ago some friends and I did a Momo crawl in Jackson heights, touring and tasting all the Momos from all the surrounding restaurants. Needless to say, this place won, and no surprise there. Their food is a flavor explosion in your mouth, and regardless of the spice and flavors, you will happily indulge in all the foods. I make a trip here from Brooklyn frequently, just to eat at this spot. If youre in Queens, definitely stop by here and try the food. You wont regret it!

Everyone has already waxed poetic about Bhanchha Ghar s momos which, they re really good, don t get me wrong but I was stupidly floored by the sel roti. Before all that though, I was a little confused, entering the restaurant. It was smaller than what I had envisioned from photographs, and there was no counter, so to speak. I just kind of helplessly looked over the wall and caught the eye of a lady cooking, asking where I should order. And right then and there, she asked me back,  What do you want to order?   Sel roti and jhol momo, please. At my request to eat in, she asked if I preferred the tables here at ground level (which were pretty tight) or the basement down the stairs. Dang, basement? I didn t know what to expect, but that s what I chose. She waved me off after I had ordered, and I assumed I just had to wait downstairs. The stairs are creaky and narrow, and they lead down to a much more spacious area. It was actually quite nice and bright, with photos of and trinkets from Nepal scattered on the walls. It was just before noon, and I saw people hunched in chairs, waiting for their meals to arrive. I chose a table and maybe 5 minutes later, the lady from above came and served me piping hot jhol momo and warm sel roti. When I first read about sel roti s description, the rice flour interested me. And when I finally bit into it, warm, soft, and crunchy from the rice flour, slightly sweet, I was pleasantly surprised. This was bread in a way I hadn t really experienced before. I had no expectations coming in, so maybe I m hyping it up too much. But that sel roti with its soft and crunchy combo and subtle sweetness accompanied the spicy jhol momo so well. I didn t know what to do with my dishes when I was done, so I waited to see what others would do once they left the basement. Apparently, you just leave them at your table and then head back upstairs, and then try to motion to her that you d like to pay. She was pretty good at remembering everyone s orders in line, and she was very proud to say that she won the Momo Crawl for two years in a row. Overall, great experience at Bhanchha Ghar. =) Jhol momo: spicy and fragrant pretty large portions. Sel roti: best $1 I ve spent in 2019 so far.

Im no expert on Nepalese food, but I loved it. That said, you pay quite a lot considering this is a real hole in the wall. The ground floor is a hole in the wall in the charming sort of way, but seating is very limited. The basement is a hole in the wall in the kinda unpleasant sort of way, but there is a lot of seating. Wai Wai sandheko ($6 for small): Dry instant noodles diced and tossed with fresh peppers and spices. Tasty. Beef jhol momo ($9): Loved the rich flavor of the chutney and the way it worked with the momo submerged in it. Chicken choila ($11): At first, I was a bit disappointed with the flavor of this seasoned chicken borderline jerky. However, as I continued to eat it I found it more and more addictive and hard to put down, and I was quite happy with it by the end. They also gave us a sel roti, which was really nice of them. Mildly sweet with rice dusting the outside of the fried dough, I found it pretty interesting, without a close, direct comparison to anything Ive had before.
